o&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Perhaps most importantly, Hill needs to reestablish Nike=E2=80=99s deep
relationships with retail partners and an understanding that great global b=
rands require multiple channels to thrive. Hill, who previously led Nike=E2=
=80=99s consumer, sales, and North American businesses, knows that the next=
 stage of growth can=E2=80=99t come from D.T.C. alone. While Nike=E2=80=99s=
 D.T.C. push made sense on paper five years ago, retail is ultimately a bus=
iness where you need to meet customers where they are shopping.
=C2=A0

Nike may have been forged as a
performance brand, but it=E2=80=99s a company built on design and distribut=
ion. Sure, they have their own stores, but they ultimately act as massive m=
arketing billboards and experiential retail. Their Well Collective concept =
stores, for instance, transform traditional retail spaces into wellness hub=
s where customers can explore fitness journeys through interactive digital =
experiences=E2=80=94and, of course, still pick up their online orders in-st=
ore. Hill gets this.
=C2=A0

He=E2=80=99s already rebuilding bridges with key wholesale partners, like D=
ick=E2=80=99s and Foot Locker. During a recent channel check, in fact, Nike=
 still had more than 50 percent of the selling floor in Foot Locker, includ=
ing an entire annex room, =E2=80=9CHouse of Hoops,=E2=80=9D that felt like =
a shrine to Jordans. After being notably absent for a spell from The Runnin=
g Event, an industry-wide trade show in San Antonio, Nike strategically ret=
urned this year with a shoe that seems to have learned a thing
or two from its competitors. The Zoom Fly 6 ( https://go.shopmy.us/p-127620=
04?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F4%2F25%29&utm_content=3DL=
ine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F4%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) features Hoka-like cushion=
ing, a move straight from the company=E2=80=99s historical playbook of obse=
rving, improving, and scaling successful innovations.
=C2=A0

After all, in Nike=E2=80=99s history, the company doesn=E2=80=99t always mo=
ve first, but it almost always finds a way to offer a superior product. A p=
erfect example, one former Nike
insider pointed out, is the Nike Pro line, a $2 billion business that start=
ed as a response to Under Armour=E2=80=99s successful introduction of =E2=
=80=9Cspandex,=E2=80=9D a.k.a. compression, into the men=E2=80=99s performa=
nce category. Under Armour may have pioneered compression wear, but Nike=E2=
=80=99s ability to scale and normalize the category turned an innovation in=
to everyday athletic wear.

=E2=80=8A

